WEBVTT

﻿1
00:00:06.000 --> 00:00:12.074
Support us and become VIP member 
to remove all ads from www.OpenSubtitles.org

2
00:00:13.888 --> 00:00:17.475
We just drove every day
looking to kill people. That's all I did.

3
00:00:17.976 --> 00:00:19.769
Every single day. I got in a car.

4
00:00:20.812 --> 00:00:23.565
looking to find somebody on the other side

5
00:00:24.941 --> 00:00:25.775
just to kill them.

6
00:00:25.859 --> 00:00:28.945
The sound of gunfire
on the streets of Philadelphia.

7
00:00:29.029 --> 00:00:32.532
as organized crime factions
have declared all-out war.

8
00:00:38.038 --> 00:00:39.205
There was no plan.

9
00:00:40.248 --> 00:00:42.208
We just shot every bullet we had.

10
00:00:44.669 --> 00:00:47.130
It was just kill.
Just… just kill. Just… just kill.

11
00:00:49.382 --> 00:00:51.801
And… that's what I did.

12
00:00:55.638 --> 00:00:58.058
Every time you turned around.
there was another killing.

13
00:00:59.309 --> 00:01:02.771
It's just more evidence
that a full-scale mob war is underway.

14
00:01:02.854 --> 00:01:04.898
The shooting started happening everywhere.

15
00:01:06.107 --> 00:01:10.403
It's one hit after the other.
more and more audacious.

16
00:01:12.155 --> 00:01:13.948
These guys are out of their fucking minds.

17
00:01:14.032 --> 00:01:16.659
It's like something out of The Godfather.

18
00:01:20.872 --> 00:01:23.416
We had to cut off the head of the snake.

19
00:01:25.752 --> 00:01:28.922
It was a huge operation.

20
00:01:29.839 --> 00:01:31.674
Failure wasn't an option.

21
00:02:03.373 --> 00:02:06.292
When people think of the Mafia.
they think of New York.

22
00:02:08.378 --> 00:02:12.757
But Philadelphia in the '90s
was 100 times more brutal.

23
00:02:12.841 --> 00:02:13.800
It's a show.

24
00:02:13.883 --> 00:02:17.220
It's a show where they kill somebody.
It's the affiliation.

25
00:02:19.180 --> 00:02:21.391
I grew up around the Gambino family.

26
00:02:21.474 --> 00:02:24.269
one of the five crime families
in New York.

27
00:02:26.563 --> 00:02:31.359
But I'd try to find excuses
to come down here to Philadelphia.

28
00:02:32.026 --> 00:02:35.947
It was just a ton of money.
a lot of fun. a lot of adrenaline.

29
00:02:36.531 --> 00:02:39.701
Prostitution. loan sharking. drugs.

30
00:02:39.784 --> 00:02:41.452
and it was 24-7.

31
00:02:42.787 --> 00:02:46.040
But the biggest thing for Mob guys
isn't just the money.

32
00:02:48.835 --> 00:02:50.211
It's the life itself.

33
00:02:51.838 --> 00:02:53.923
Philadelphia guys are
like the Little Rascals.

34
00:02:54.007 --> 00:02:55.341
They're a wild bunch of guys.

35
00:02:57.468 --> 00:02:59.220
Shooting shots all day.

36
00:03:00.180 --> 00:03:01.723
Stay out all night.

37
00:03:03.183 --> 00:03:05.852
They all grew up
on the same block in South Philly.

38
00:03:07.061 --> 00:03:08.438
These guys are tight-knit.

39
00:03:09.355 --> 00:03:12.984
In the Philly Mob.
everybody knows everybody somehow.

40
00:03:13.067 --> 00:03:16.654
Everybody is just one way
or another connected.

41
00:03:17.280 --> 00:03:19.157
And it was fun. honestly. back then.

42
00:03:19.908 --> 00:03:23.745
If you were associated with the Mob.
you could do whatever you want.

43
00:03:23.828 --> 00:03:26.164
You pull up in a brand-new Cadillac.

44
00:03:27.957 --> 00:03:30.668
You wanna go into a club.
you go in the front.

45
00:03:31.169 --> 00:03:32.712
It was really fun.

46
00:03:34.839 --> 00:03:37.759
Guys in New York would bad-mouth
the Philadelphia Mob.

47
00:03:38.259 --> 00:03:40.845
They'd say. "I can send down two killers
and finish them off."

48
00:03:40.929 --> 00:03:44.724
And I'd laugh. I'd say. "Listen.
you guys don't know these guys.

49
00:03:44.807 --> 00:03:45.934
and they're dangerous."

50
00:03:48.561 --> 00:03:51.814
Frankie "Stale" Stillitano
found stuffed in a car trunk.

51
00:03:52.315 --> 00:03:54.984
Mob murders are becoming almost routine.

52
00:03:57.403 --> 00:04:00.323
Philly guys held up their own
against anybody. any crew.

53
00:04:01.199 --> 00:04:03.993
New York. Chicago. you name it.

54
00:04:04.786 --> 00:04:08.498
If they had to go up to bat. they'd bat.
They hit the ball.

55
00:04:13.461 --> 00:04:17.674
But what makes Philadelphia different
than New York is Atlantic City.

56
00:04:17.757 --> 00:04:19.759
Atlantic City was always
Philly's territory.

57
00:04:21.261 --> 00:04:24.013
And when casinos came.
we started to see dollar signs.

58
00:04:25.056 --> 00:04:28.226
All the hotels. the gambling.
the construction.

59
00:04:28.309 --> 00:04:30.186
It was a ton of money for the Mob.

60
00:04:31.688 --> 00:04:35.858
And at the time. the boss of Philadelphia
and Atlantic City was Nicky Scarfo.

61
00:04:37.986 --> 00:04:40.655
Nicky Scarfo was a psychopath.

62
00:04:42.782 --> 00:04:45.159
I put 40 years in law enforcement.

63
00:04:46.494 --> 00:04:50.873
and he's the most vicious person
I've experienced in my life.

64
00:04:51.582 --> 00:04:53.334
But I'll give you an example.

65
00:04:54.794 --> 00:04:57.547
He killed a man with a butter knife.

66
00:04:58.256 --> 00:04:59.674
It's a butter knife.

67
00:04:59.757 --> 00:05:02.719
and you know the kind of force
you have to use

68
00:05:02.802 --> 00:05:05.430
to penetrate the human body
with a butter knife?

69
00:05:06.180 --> 00:05:08.308
-How you doing?
-Nothing to say.

70
00:05:08.391 --> 00:05:09.809
I'm innocent. That's all.

71
00:05:10.977 --> 00:05:14.605
There was a lot of violence going on
in South Philly when Nicky was in charge.

72
00:05:14.689 --> 00:05:17.525
It was basically like the Wild Wild West.
Bang 'em up. shoot 'em up.

73
00:05:17.608 --> 00:05:18.985
Bodies were flying everywhere.

74
00:05:23.489 --> 00:05:25.491
He was ruthless. He was paranoid.

75
00:05:25.575 --> 00:05:27.618
Every time you turned around.
another killing.

76
00:05:29.787 --> 00:05:34.959
Nicky Scarfo. he was the most paranoid
Mob boss. cokehead.

77
00:05:35.626 --> 00:05:37.170
that I could fucking think of.

78
00:05:38.796 --> 00:05:43.217
The guys are found in cars and dumpsters
and on the sidewalk.

79
00:05:43.760 --> 00:05:46.179
Come on. You know. you don't do that.

80
00:05:46.262 --> 00:05:48.139
You don't want the bodies found.

81
00:05:48.723 --> 00:05:50.975
because once the public turns against you.

82
00:05:51.642 --> 00:05:54.145
then that's when the FBI get involved.

83
00:05:55.563 --> 00:05:57.148
And then after that.

84
00:05:58.733 --> 00:05:59.650
it's over.

85
00:06:00.485 --> 00:06:03.946
Indicted today.
38 alleged key Mob figures.

86
00:06:04.030 --> 00:06:05.782
among them Nicodemo Scarfo.

87
00:06:06.574 --> 00:06:08.284
What do you do for a living?

88
00:06:08.951 --> 00:06:11.537
I invoke my right
under the Fifth Amendment

89
00:06:11.621 --> 00:06:16.167
of the United States Constitution
and decline to answer the question.

90
00:06:16.250 --> 00:06:20.088
Nicky Scarfo is currently serving
a 55-year sentence in federal prison.

91
00:06:20.171 --> 00:06:22.131
The demise of the Scarfo crime family

92
00:06:22.215 --> 00:06:26.552
has now opened up
the Philadelphia Atlantic City underworlds

93
00:06:26.636 --> 00:06:31.224
to the expanding interest of New York
and Sicilian Mafia kingpins.

94
00:06:31.307 --> 00:06:34.727
So who is controlling
the Philadelphia Atlantic City Mob?

95
00:06:34.811 --> 00:06:37.563
Who. if anyone.
is operating for La Cosa Nostra?

96
00:06:46.197 --> 00:06:49.617
In 1991. I was appointed the supervisor

97
00:06:49.700 --> 00:06:52.662
for the organized crime program
in Philadelphia.

98
00:06:54.622 --> 00:06:58.376
There had never been a woman in the field

99
00:06:58.459 --> 00:07:00.628
as an organized-crime supervisor.

100
00:07:04.507 --> 00:07:07.593
When I arrived. Scarfo was gone.

101
00:07:07.677 --> 00:07:11.806
And with Scarfo in jail.
there was a power vacuum.

102
00:07:11.889 --> 00:07:16.269
So my job was to find out
who was going to be the new boss.

103
00:07:19.272 --> 00:07:20.731
But where do you begin?

104
00:07:24.068 --> 00:07:26.529
I've been in this business a long time.

105
00:07:26.612 --> 00:07:29.532
When it comes to taking down the Mob.

106
00:07:30.408 --> 00:07:33.077
nothing beats gumshoe.

107
00:07:38.624 --> 00:07:41.169
You've got to get out on the street.

108
00:07:41.669 --> 00:07:43.171
make informants.

109
00:07:43.254 --> 00:07:45.548
and get the information you need.

110
00:07:48.384 --> 00:07:53.181
We didn't have much in the way
of informants at that particular point.

111
00:07:53.264 --> 00:07:55.850
and you can't work organized crime
without informants.

112
00:07:57.185 --> 00:07:58.561
But then. one day.

113
00:07:58.644 --> 00:08:03.149
the Philadelphia Police Department
arrested. like. a low-level criminal

114
00:08:03.232 --> 00:08:04.942
associated with the Mob.

115
00:08:06.402 --> 00:08:09.947
It was street shakedowns.
extorting businesses.

116
00:08:10.031 --> 00:08:12.116
nothing real sophisticated.

117
00:08:14.994 --> 00:08:18.206
This guy was a soldier in the Philly Mob.

118
00:08:19.123 --> 00:08:21.751
So he knew who's in charge now.

119
00:08:26.172 --> 00:08:28.966
When you get them cornered.
they're gonna talk.

120
00:08:29.050 --> 00:08:30.384
They wanna make a deal.

121
00:08:30.468 --> 00:08:34.263
These are big. tough guys.
crying to give you information.

122
00:08:34.347 --> 00:08:35.890
They don't wanna go to jail.

123
00:08:37.892 --> 00:08:43.439
So when they talk about this honor
and loyalty and all this omertà.

124
00:08:43.523 --> 00:08:45.650
it's a bunch of tripe.

125
00:08:45.733 --> 00:08:48.736
They're all quote-unquote "rats."

126
00:08:51.405 --> 00:08:53.908
According to this informant.

127
00:08:54.408 --> 00:08:59.288
there was a power vacuum.
but that vacuum was filled pretty quick…

128
00:09:01.541 --> 00:09:03.751
by a guy called John Stanfa.

129
00:09:04.919 --> 00:09:07.046
But who is John Stanfa?

130
00:09:11.008 --> 00:09:13.010
When John Stanfa's name surfaces.

131
00:09:13.094 --> 00:09:15.805
he's probably in his early fifties
somewhere.

132
00:09:15.888 --> 00:09:17.807
You know. he's from Sicily. a made guy.

133
00:09:18.432 --> 00:09:22.186
And he was getting the backing
of the five families in New York.

134
00:09:23.604 --> 00:09:25.815
John Stanfa was old-school.

135
00:09:26.524 --> 00:09:30.653
And the old-school Mafia was
make money. not headlines.

136
00:09:31.862 --> 00:09:35.157
And the five families trusted John Stanfa

137
00:09:35.241 --> 00:09:41.247
to try to calm down the violence
seen under Nicky Scarfo

138
00:09:41.330 --> 00:09:44.417
and bring back order
to the Philadelphia family.

139
00:09:45.710 --> 00:09:47.336
If he's the boss of the family.

140
00:09:47.420 --> 00:09:50.590
he's got to be directing
criminal activities.

141
00:09:50.673 --> 00:09:52.717
And we didn't know what they were

142
00:09:52.800 --> 00:09:56.637
because he was just a guy
who was going to work every day.

143
00:09:58.598 --> 00:10:02.268
He lived in a very nice house
over in New Jersey.

144
00:10:02.351 --> 00:10:05.646
He was picked up by his chauffeur
in the morning.

145
00:10:06.439 --> 00:10:10.693
And he had a business
called Continental Foods.

146
00:10:11.652 --> 00:10:16.616
But we didn't have any sort of crime
to attach to him.

147
00:10:19.785 --> 00:10:22.580
So that made my job harder.

148
00:10:27.460 --> 00:10:32.006
We started looking at the guys
that might be working for him.

149
00:10:35.051 --> 00:10:39.347
Loan sharks. petty thieves. bookmakers.

150
00:10:39.847 --> 00:10:42.308
Basically low-level soldiers

151
00:10:42.391 --> 00:10:45.353
bringing in the money
and kicking it up to the boss.

152
00:10:48.773 --> 00:10:52.193
That's when we found the bookmaker.

153
00:10:54.111 --> 00:10:56.739
Through our sources.
we picked up information

154
00:10:56.822 --> 00:10:59.742
that this guy was gonna be meeting Stanfa…

155
00:11:01.661 --> 00:11:03.913
…at Salvatore Avena's office.

156
00:11:04.664 --> 00:11:08.376
Avena was a long-standing Mob lawyer.

157
00:11:09.585 --> 00:11:12.421
We set up. uh. a camera on the front

158
00:11:12.505 --> 00:11:16.384
so that we could tape
what was going on every day

159
00:11:16.467 --> 00:11:18.719
in front of that law office.

160
00:11:22.264 --> 00:11:25.726
Sal was well-known. Philly. South Jersey.
everybody knew who he was.

161
00:11:26.727 --> 00:11:29.689
He handled a lot
of high-profile Mob cases.

162
00:11:31.399 --> 00:11:34.860
And he would have a lot of guys
coming in all the time.

163
00:11:39.448 --> 00:11:43.411
And eventually.
Stanfa shows up in that office.

164
00:11:45.705 --> 00:11:51.585
My gut was telling me Stanfa's using
that office for criminal activities.

165
00:11:53.254 --> 00:11:55.339
You just knew something was going on.

166
00:11:56.799 --> 00:12:01.137
He started having his meetings
thinking it's a safe haven legally

167
00:12:01.220 --> 00:12:03.556
under client-attorney privilege.

168
00:12:06.308 --> 00:12:10.563
But you know what? If you're
using a law office to commit crime.

169
00:12:11.188 --> 00:12:13.023
you lose that privilege.

170
00:12:15.651 --> 00:12:18.195
I was working as a federal prosecutor.

171
00:12:18.821 --> 00:12:21.449
The FBI came to me and said.

172
00:12:21.532 --> 00:12:23.200
"If you have the guts.

173
00:12:24.076 --> 00:12:25.286
we think we have enough

174
00:12:25.369 --> 00:12:27.371
to bug Sal Avena's office."

175
00:12:30.166 --> 00:12:36.213
And I said. "You're asking a judge
to authorize a surreptitious entry

176
00:12:36.297 --> 00:12:40.593
into a respected
criminal defense lawyer's office

177
00:12:41.177 --> 00:12:43.512
to put microphones in that office."

178
00:12:44.263 --> 00:12:47.475
"So you're really asking that judge
to go out on a limb."

179
00:12:48.392 --> 00:12:50.728
"Okay.""This is…"

180
00:12:51.562 --> 00:12:53.939
"Yes. I guess I have to have the guts."

181
00:12:55.441 --> 00:12:57.985
I thought we had a really good case.

182
00:12:59.820 --> 00:13:04.200
And as it turned out.
the judge agreed with me.

183
00:13:06.869 --> 00:13:09.163
Once you get that affidavit approved.

184
00:13:09.246 --> 00:13:12.333
you want to get up and running
really. really fast.

185
00:13:12.958 --> 00:13:14.877
You don't want to miss anything.

186
00:13:18.422 --> 00:13:21.967
And so the pressure is on the tech guys.

187
00:13:23.552 --> 00:13:26.639
People don't realize.
you just don't wake up one day and say.

188
00:13:26.722 --> 00:13:29.934
"Hey. go bug Sal Avena's office.
Here's a microphone."

189
00:13:30.017 --> 00:13:31.101
And you walk in and do it.

190
00:13:32.978 --> 00:13:34.146
It takes a lot.

191
00:13:34.939 --> 00:13:36.398
Getting prepared. watching.

192
00:13:36.482 --> 00:13:39.777
making sure the comings and goings
for a week or two before.

193
00:13:40.402 --> 00:13:41.529
It was a big operation.

194
00:13:45.741 --> 00:13:47.409
The night of the job.

195
00:13:47.952 --> 00:13:49.495
I was incredibly anxious

196
00:13:49.578 --> 00:13:53.207
because if the bugging operation failed.

197
00:13:53.290 --> 00:13:55.584
it's like. what is your alternative?

198
00:13:55.668 --> 00:13:58.254
I mean. we would be back to square one.

199
00:13:59.338 --> 00:14:02.258
We were dropped off
at the building after midnight.

200
00:14:05.803 --> 00:14:08.264
Within a few seconds. we were inside.

201
00:14:09.473 --> 00:14:11.892
And laser focused on our job.

202
00:14:15.145 --> 00:14:17.648
Sal Avena's offices were
on the second floor.

203
00:14:22.444 --> 00:14:24.363
There was a door with an alarm panel.

204
00:14:29.910 --> 00:14:32.204
The lock and alarm guys
were able to bypass the alarm.

205
00:14:34.081 --> 00:14:35.416
And they're in.

206
00:14:41.964 --> 00:14:45.551
We had to determine
where can we place this microphone

207
00:14:45.634 --> 00:14:49.471
where it has airspace
so that it can pick up conversations

208
00:14:49.555 --> 00:14:51.140
but it can't be easily found?

209
00:14:54.435 --> 00:14:56.937
I was in the basement connecting wires.

210
00:14:58.522 --> 00:14:59.773
We were almost done.

211
00:15:01.567 --> 00:15:02.610
And all of a sudden…

212
00:15:06.780 --> 00:15:09.533
I got word that someone was coming
into the building.

213
00:15:18.334 --> 00:15:22.338
We realized one of the lock and alarm guys
had dropped their bags

214
00:15:22.421 --> 00:15:24.423
in the vestibule of the building.

215
00:15:28.260 --> 00:15:32.890
Is this guy gonna look in these bags
and find tools and equipment

216
00:15:34.058 --> 00:15:36.060
and then come down and find us?

217
00:16:00.376 --> 00:16:03.462
Finally. they stepped back
over the bags and left.

218
00:16:06.423 --> 00:16:10.386
Why he didn't look at the bags
or say something. we'll never know.

219
00:16:11.178 --> 00:16:12.304
Our luck was good that day.

220
00:16:29.405 --> 00:16:31.782
When they finally called me. I was having

221
00:16:31.865 --> 00:16:34.243
my second glass of wine.

222
00:16:34.326 --> 00:16:36.829
And then it's like. "Yes! Yes."

223
00:16:36.912 --> 00:16:38.580
"Oh. thank God."

224
00:16:38.664 --> 00:16:42.251
"Okay. we're gonna be up and running.
Everybody's fine."

225
00:16:50.718 --> 00:16:52.761
Once we were listening.

226
00:16:52.845 --> 00:16:57.099
we only have 30 days to prove
that they're involved in crimes.

227
00:16:57.599 --> 00:16:59.768
Otherwise.
you have to shut everything down.

228
00:17:04.356 --> 00:17:07.484
Now you have to intercept
criminal conversations

229
00:17:08.027 --> 00:17:10.529
to justify to the judge

230
00:17:11.280 --> 00:17:14.074
that the surveillance.
uh. should continue.

231
00:17:18.996 --> 00:17:23.042
And I had agents sitting
in the squad area with reel-to-reels

232
00:17:23.125 --> 00:17:25.252
listening to tapes all the time.

233
00:17:35.345 --> 00:17:37.097
We were working around the clock.

234
00:17:39.016 --> 00:17:40.476
Taking handwritten notes.

235
00:17:43.771 --> 00:17:46.857
If you have two or three people
talking at the same time.

236
00:17:46.940 --> 00:17:48.525
that can be very difficult.

237
00:17:48.609 --> 00:17:50.319
Yeah. Kill them.

238
00:17:50.402 --> 00:17:51.570
You being serious?

239
00:17:51.653 --> 00:17:52.905
Kill them…

240
00:17:54.782 --> 00:17:56.450
We weren't picking up that much.

241
00:17:56.533 --> 00:17:59.453
and what we were picking up
wasn't sufficient.

242
00:18:02.581 --> 00:18:04.374
What's going on? How's everything?

243
00:18:04.458 --> 00:18:05.834
Good. You sound bad.

244
00:18:05.918 --> 00:18:06.752
Yeah.

245
00:18:07.377 --> 00:18:09.088
What are you. nasally or what?

246
00:18:09.588 --> 00:18:15.219
They were just. like. shooting the breeze.
and no business was being transacted.

247
00:18:16.512 --> 00:18:19.264
A lot of work went into this.

248
00:18:19.932 --> 00:18:21.934
Months of investigation.

249
00:18:22.559 --> 00:18:25.479
And if it turns out
no one's going in there to talk.

250
00:18:25.562 --> 00:18:26.855
well. that's all wasted.

251
00:18:29.525 --> 00:18:32.861
So the frustration was building.

252
00:18:35.489 --> 00:18:37.658
We had six days left.

253
00:18:39.284 --> 00:18:40.953
And we didn't have anything.

254
00:18:42.371 --> 00:18:46.333
If we didn't come up with something
during that six-day period.

255
00:18:46.416 --> 00:18:49.461
we were gonna
have to shut the operation down.

256
00:18:51.004 --> 00:18:53.090
All that work. all that effort.

257
00:18:53.173 --> 00:18:56.468
and it's like.
we gotta get lucky here or something.

258
00:19:02.641 --> 00:19:05.477
And then. on December 3rd. 1991.

259
00:19:06.270 --> 00:19:12.568
the surveillance cameras showed
John Stanfa going into Sal Avena's office.

260
00:19:19.867 --> 00:19:22.035
The case agent called me and said.

261
00:19:22.119 --> 00:19:23.662
"I think we've got something."

262
00:19:24.830 --> 00:19:27.249
And I read the transcript.

263
00:19:28.584 --> 00:19:33.297
Stanfa. "We don't want quantity.
We want quality."

264
00:19:33.380 --> 00:19:37.509
"Just because a guy.
maybe he is a good earner.

265
00:19:37.593 --> 00:19:41.597
or this or that. I can't go for that.
You know what I mean?"

266
00:19:42.139 --> 00:19:43.807
"I don't go for no money."

267
00:19:44.349 --> 00:19:49.271
"I no hungry for money
because Cosa Nostra. it's not for money."

268
00:19:49.354 --> 00:19:50.814
"Cosa Nostra."

269
00:19:52.149 --> 00:19:52.983
Key word.

270
00:19:53.650 --> 00:19:55.194
My reaction was.

271
00:19:55.277 --> 00:19:58.822
"Oh my God. this evidence is amazing."

272
00:19:59.489 --> 00:20:03.994
Finally. finally. we got what we need.

273
00:20:08.457 --> 00:20:11.210
Here you have.
one of the first times ever.

274
00:20:11.293 --> 00:20:15.714
some Mob guy was actually saying
that term on tape.

275
00:20:15.797 --> 00:20:18.717
The thing that you have to realize is

276
00:20:19.635 --> 00:20:22.971
any Mob guy that was arrested.
the defense was.

277
00:20:23.055 --> 00:20:27.351
"There's no such thing as La Cosa Nostra.
There's no Mob."

278
00:20:27.935 --> 00:20:29.228
"This is just a social club

279
00:20:29.311 --> 00:20:32.814
with. you know.
older Italians playing cards."

280
00:20:33.440 --> 00:20:38.528
The defense was to deny
that this organization existed.

281
00:20:40.155 --> 00:20:43.116
Well. now you have
the boss of the family talking about.

282
00:20:43.200 --> 00:20:47.162
"This isn't Cosa Nostra.
We want quality. not quantity."

283
00:20:47.246 --> 00:20:48.622
He's laying it out.

284
00:20:48.705 --> 00:20:50.040
"This is what I want."

285
00:20:50.958 --> 00:20:52.292
"And I'm not getting it."

286
00:20:52.376 --> 00:20:56.213
And so. he's confirming
that he's the one in charge.

287
00:20:58.173 --> 00:20:59.967
So we went from zero to.

288
00:21:00.509 --> 00:21:03.178
"Wow. we might have a case here."

289
00:21:07.557 --> 00:21:11.895
We thought that the Avena office
was gonna be our gold mine.

290
00:21:12.604 --> 00:21:14.940
And I just really felt.

291
00:21:15.607 --> 00:21:18.819
"We have a chance here
to have another major takedown

292
00:21:18.902 --> 00:21:21.697
of the Philadelphia. uh. Mob."

293
00:21:26.076 --> 00:21:28.829
Everyone was working hard.

294
00:21:29.830 --> 00:21:33.208
And we were getting
such good intelligence on Stanfa.

295
00:21:35.502 --> 00:21:36.712
But also.

296
00:21:37.713 --> 00:21:41.383
we got information
that was really shocking.

297
00:21:48.265 --> 00:21:50.434
It seemed like Stanfa had enemies.

298
00:21:53.979 --> 00:21:59.568
Not everyone was happy
that he was the boss of the family.

299
00:22:00.986 --> 00:22:02.446
Stanfa was intercepted saying.

300
00:22:02.529 --> 00:22:04.823
"These guys.
they basically have no respect."

301
00:22:04.906 --> 00:22:06.783
"They call us greaseballs."

302
00:22:12.914 --> 00:22:16.001
According to word on the street.

303
00:22:16.710 --> 00:22:20.714
the younger guys in Philadelphia.
they didn't respect John Stanfa.

304
00:22:20.797 --> 00:22:22.257
He was an outsider.

305
00:22:23.300 --> 00:22:26.345
And that created a lot of conflict.

306
00:22:29.723 --> 00:22:33.477
When I opened the case.
we code-named it "Young Guns."

307
00:22:34.353 --> 00:22:36.938
During the course of our investigation.

308
00:22:37.022 --> 00:22:42.736
we determined that this group
was being led by Joey Merlino.

309
00:22:43.862 --> 00:22:46.907
Joey's father and his uncle
were organized crime.

310
00:22:46.990 --> 00:22:49.034
Joey was pedigree.

311
00:22:49.117 --> 00:22:52.079
He associated himself
with Michael Ciancaglini.

312
00:22:53.163 --> 00:22:56.875
You did not want to cross paths
with Michael Ciancaglini.

313
00:22:56.958 --> 00:22:58.919
Uh. tough kid.

314
00:23:00.879 --> 00:23:04.674
Joey and Michael Ciancaglini.
they were best friends.

315
00:23:05.175 --> 00:23:08.345
and they created their own little army.

316
00:23:12.349 --> 00:23:14.976
Joey Merlino and his crew were GQ.

317
00:23:16.311 --> 00:23:19.398
Wearing Gucci. Prada.

318
00:23:20.440 --> 00:23:22.901
And they're flamboyant. They throw it out.

319
00:23:23.985 --> 00:23:27.072
The old-time guys didn't care about that.

320
00:23:27.155 --> 00:23:32.119
That's exactly the opposite
that organized crime used to stand for.

321
00:23:33.078 --> 00:23:36.415
Everybody liked Joey
because Joey was a personable guy.

322
00:23:36.998 --> 00:23:39.418
Dressed well. He drove nice cars.

323
00:23:39.501 --> 00:23:41.128
You know. he was a handsome guy.

324
00:23:41.795 --> 00:23:43.171
We went to school together.

325
00:23:43.672 --> 00:23:46.591
He used to rob the lunch money
and stuff like that.

326
00:23:47.092 --> 00:23:48.552
Joey was wild.

327
00:23:49.219 --> 00:23:50.804
Good guy. Just crazy.

328
00:23:51.847 --> 00:23:52.931
We grew up together.

329
00:23:53.014 --> 00:23:54.433
That's what made us unique.

330
00:23:54.516 --> 00:23:55.684
We were all friends.

331
00:23:55.767 --> 00:23:58.437
whether it was
at the highest level. "supposedly."

332
00:23:58.520 --> 00:24:00.814
or just measly bookmakers like myself.

333
00:24:00.897 --> 00:24:02.399
You know. we all trusted each other.

334
00:24:03.442 --> 00:24:06.194
Joey could pickpocket you.
and you would say. "Thank you."

335
00:24:07.362 --> 00:24:09.906
You know. it was just his personality.

336
00:24:09.990 --> 00:24:11.491
You know. he had a way about himself.

337
00:24:12.075 --> 00:24:14.744
Joey's character to me.
and I'll put it this way.

338
00:24:14.828 --> 00:24:18.039
his own guys
shouldn't fall asleep near him.

339
00:24:18.123 --> 00:24:21.168
He would go in their pockets
and steal their money

340
00:24:21.668 --> 00:24:23.587
while they're whacked out sleeping.

341
00:24:23.670 --> 00:24:27.340
So when they woke up the next day
and they're hungover from hell.

342
00:24:27.424 --> 00:24:28.925
they don't know where their money went.

343
00:24:29.009 --> 00:24:31.928
Joey's like. "You spent it.
You were buying everybody drinks."

344
00:24:34.556 --> 00:24:36.641
You're not gonna get young guys

345
00:24:36.725 --> 00:24:40.187
listen to a guy
that's come in from Sicily into the States

346
00:24:40.270 --> 00:24:43.231
telling the guys in Philadelphia.
"You're gonna listen to me now."

347
00:24:45.859 --> 00:24:47.527
To me. Stanfa was a zip.

348
00:24:48.862 --> 00:24:51.865
That's the term
that most high-end Americans use

349
00:24:51.948 --> 00:24:54.242
for people that are born across in Italy.

350
00:24:54.326 --> 00:24:55.202
They're zips.

351
00:24:55.785 --> 00:24:59.915
Stanfa could have Sicilian mentality
and old school and everything.

352
00:24:59.998 --> 00:25:01.833
but it doesn't work here in America.

353
00:25:01.917 --> 00:25:04.252
His old school don't work here in America.

354
00:25:04.336 --> 00:25:07.756
His Sicilian mentality
don't work here in America.

355
00:25:09.007 --> 00:25:13.803
The Young Turks. they were. you know.
rough-and-tumble street kids.

356
00:25:13.887 --> 00:25:16.598
Very immature. prone to violence.

357
00:25:17.265 --> 00:25:20.477
extorting businesses and drug dealers.

358
00:25:20.560 --> 00:25:22.812
And they're gonna make
a name for themselves.

359
00:25:22.896 --> 00:25:24.397
They wanted to be famous.

360
00:25:28.276 --> 00:25:32.822
And a number of their fathers
had been high-level people

361
00:25:32.906 --> 00:25:35.700
in the Scarfo organization

362
00:25:35.784 --> 00:25:38.537
and were gonna be in jail
the rest of their lives.

363
00:25:40.038 --> 00:25:42.499
They felt their fathers
had paid their dues.

364
00:25:42.582 --> 00:25:45.544
and now it was their time.
and this was their birthright.

365
00:25:49.214 --> 00:25:53.218
John Stanfa terribly misunderstood
this situation.

366
00:25:53.301 --> 00:25:58.932
He didn't understand the thirst
that Joey Merlino and his crew had

367
00:25:59.599 --> 00:26:01.810
to get control of Philadelphia.

368
00:26:04.813 --> 00:26:08.358
Joey was very capable of going
and putting a gun in his pants by himself.

369
00:26:08.441 --> 00:26:10.735
get in the car.
and go take care of business.

370
00:26:12.445 --> 00:26:13.822
So I respect him for it.

371
00:26:15.740 --> 00:26:17.826
You know. you're a gangster
who's really a gangster.

372
00:26:20.287 --> 00:26:22.872
John Stanfa was never gonna
tell Joey what to do.

373
00:26:24.874 --> 00:26:28.128
John Stanfa made a big mistake
coming to Philly.

374
00:26:39.639 --> 00:26:42.225
72-year-old Felix Bocchino
was found this morning

375
00:26:42.309 --> 00:26:45.312
at the wheel of his car
on the 1.200 block of Mifflin Street.

376
00:26:45.395 --> 00:26:46.980
He'd been shot three times.

377
00:26:47.063 --> 00:26:50.108
The police say it has all the signs
of a classic Mob hit.

378
00:26:50.191 --> 00:26:53.987
It happened very quickly.
A person. or persons. came up to the car.

379
00:26:54.070 --> 00:26:57.240
It was. uh. close range.
and they fled immediately afterwards.

380
00:26:59.242 --> 00:27:01.328
We hadn't had a Mob hit in seven years.

381
00:27:01.411 --> 00:27:04.914
and now here's a Mob hit in the morning.

382
00:27:04.998 --> 00:27:06.833
broad daylight. South Philadelphia.

383
00:27:11.838 --> 00:27:14.424
Felix Bocchino was an old-time bookmaker.

384
00:27:15.425 --> 00:27:17.260
and part of the Stanfa organization.

385
00:27:18.053 --> 00:27:21.473
It's a gangland hit. clearly.
He still had money in his pocket.

386
00:27:23.141 --> 00:27:24.851
As a former Mob reporter.

387
00:27:24.934 --> 00:27:26.936
this is the way hits go down.

388
00:27:27.020 --> 00:27:29.606
You hate to say it was
very efficient and smooth. but it was.

389
00:27:29.689 --> 00:27:31.316
It was a very efficient and smooth hit.

390
00:27:32.275 --> 00:27:35.362
Organized-crime watchers
say it at least signals a turning point

391
00:27:35.445 --> 00:27:38.239
as the Philadelphia Mob enters a new era.

392
00:27:39.532 --> 00:27:40.742
In my opinion.

393
00:27:41.618 --> 00:27:44.996
it was a statement by Joey Merlino

394
00:27:45.080 --> 00:27:49.292
that we are not gonna
follow you. John Stanfa.

395
00:27:50.710 --> 00:27:52.128
It was a coup d'état.

396
00:27:52.212 --> 00:27:54.923
John Stanfa just did not know
how to handle that.

397
00:27:55.840 --> 00:27:59.886
But he wanted to get retaliation.
There's no question about that.

398
00:28:02.430 --> 00:28:04.265
Last night. police say two gunmen

399
00:28:04.349 --> 00:28:06.393
pumped five shotgun rounds into the house.

400
00:28:06.976 --> 00:28:09.604
narrowly missing
29-year-old Michael Ciancaglini.

401
00:28:09.688 --> 00:28:11.523
his wife. and two children.

402
00:28:12.732 --> 00:28:15.652
Michael's Joey Merlino's top lieutenant.

403
00:28:16.736 --> 00:28:19.114
This was a message from Stanfa.

404
00:28:21.449 --> 00:28:23.910
I mean. you're firing shotguns
in the neighborhood.

405
00:28:23.993 --> 00:28:25.578
There are people all around.

406
00:28:25.662 --> 00:28:26.579
What are you doing?

407
00:28:29.708 --> 00:28:32.752
This was unprecedented.
and it was shocking.

408
00:28:33.837 --> 00:28:36.798
Traditionally.
Cosa Nostra in the United States

409
00:28:36.881 --> 00:28:38.508
would not attack family.

410
00:28:39.384 --> 00:28:42.429
It showed that whoever did it
had no regard

411
00:28:43.346 --> 00:28:47.726
for what had been the so-called rules.
if there's rules about killing people.

412
00:28:48.309 --> 00:28:49.644
It was just craziness.

413
00:28:50.895 --> 00:28:52.480
And it had to be stopped.

414
00:28:53.356 --> 00:28:57.485
That's your worst nightmare
because they do this on the streets.

415
00:28:57.986 --> 00:29:01.030
so it's like the public can be in danger.

416
00:29:01.740 --> 00:29:05.618
How do we contain this
so that we don't have more violence?

417
00:29:11.207 --> 00:29:12.834
The whole time we're investigating.

418
00:29:12.917 --> 00:29:14.335
and we have a wiretap up.

419
00:29:14.419 --> 00:29:18.298
The agents and everybody was trying
to figure out what was gonna go on.

420
00:29:19.716 --> 00:29:23.303
Then we get this interception
December 1st. 1992.

421
00:29:51.039 --> 00:29:53.792
Stanfa says.
"We're going to start the war."

422
00:29:54.584 --> 00:29:55.543
Oh my God.

423
00:29:57.504 --> 00:30:00.673
You have two sides
actively trying to kill each other.

424
00:30:02.217 --> 00:30:05.428
As dangerous as Scarfo was.
that's even more dangerous

425
00:30:05.512 --> 00:30:09.599
because Scarfo.
you just had this homicidal maniac.

426
00:30:09.682 --> 00:30:12.602
Now. if you double that.
you have a real problem.

427
00:30:13.686 --> 00:30:17.774
I had to get Stanfa
and his crew off the street

428
00:30:17.857 --> 00:30:20.568
without more people getting hurt.

429
00:30:21.236 --> 00:30:23.613
So we need more intelligence on them.

430
00:30:25.782 --> 00:30:29.911
My division was working hard
to develop information on Stanfa.

431
00:30:29.994 --> 00:30:32.455
and we would share it with the FBI.

432
00:30:35.083 --> 00:30:40.421
Street word was John Stanfa
made Joey Ciancaglini his underboss.

433
00:30:42.549 --> 00:30:46.135
Joey Ciancaglini.
he's the brother of Michael Ciancaglini.

434
00:30:46.219 --> 00:30:48.596
who John Stanfa tried to murder.

435
00:30:49.973 --> 00:30:51.933
It is the City of Brotherly Love.

436
00:30:52.016 --> 00:30:53.726
and you have two brothers

437
00:30:53.810 --> 00:30:57.272
who are on the opposite sides
trying to kill one another.

438
00:30:59.232 --> 00:31:03.611
Stanfa owned a restaurant
called the Warfield Diner.

439
00:31:04.779 --> 00:31:08.199
And his underboss. Joey Ciancaglini.
was the manager.

440
00:31:09.075 --> 00:31:11.786
We set up a camera on the front

441
00:31:11.870 --> 00:31:15.373
so that we could watch him 24 hours a day.

442
00:31:16.875 --> 00:31:21.796
Stanfa was spending
quite a bit of time at the diner.

443
00:31:23.715 --> 00:31:28.469
Then we got authorization
to put a microphone inside.

444
00:31:31.097 --> 00:31:33.725
The Warfield Diner
opened early in the morning.

445
00:31:35.059 --> 00:31:39.939
And so we figured we'd have a window
of maybe… maybe three hours

446
00:31:40.023 --> 00:31:41.232
to do the work in there.

447
00:31:41.316 --> 00:31:44.402
So we would get our equipment prepared.

448
00:31:44.485 --> 00:31:47.864
and we figured four o'clock
would be the latest to get out of there.

449
00:31:51.451 --> 00:31:53.119
I was incredibly anxious

450
00:31:53.202 --> 00:31:56.706
because this team is going to do something

451
00:31:56.789 --> 00:31:58.958
where their lives could be in danger.

452
00:32:01.002 --> 00:32:04.172
Whenever you do any of these operations.
and this one specifically. you're…

453
00:32:04.255 --> 00:32:06.424
you know. you're geared up for it.
You're. uh…

454
00:32:06.507 --> 00:32:08.092
You're on edge. You're a little nervous.

455
00:32:08.176 --> 00:32:11.262
You're hoping that everything goes well
and nobody sees you.

456
00:32:13.056 --> 00:32:16.476
It was a Mob hangout.
so they're probably armed.

457
00:32:17.060 --> 00:32:18.686
And of course we're armed.

458
00:32:18.770 --> 00:32:22.941
And we don't want this
to turn into an ugly situation.

459
00:32:36.245 --> 00:32:38.122
We put in the microphones.

460
00:32:38.206 --> 00:32:39.832
Everything's working fine.

461
00:32:41.834 --> 00:32:44.379
And once we're done.
we started tidying up.

462
00:32:49.926 --> 00:32:53.221
My whole group. it's like.
"Okay. we're ready to go."

463
00:32:53.304 --> 00:32:55.014
"We're ready to monitor this thing."

464
00:32:58.101 --> 00:32:59.560
That first morning.

465
00:32:59.644 --> 00:33:01.938
one of the agents
was in the listening post.

466
00:33:03.606 --> 00:33:06.025
All of a sudden. he hears…

467
00:33:17.996 --> 00:33:19.998
The phone went off next to my bed.

468
00:33:20.081 --> 00:33:23.126
I looked at the time.
and it was. like. 6:00 a.m.

469
00:33:23.626 --> 00:33:25.461
And then I thought. "Oh no."

470
00:33:25.545 --> 00:33:28.256
"Are you telling me
that one of the tech guys is hurt?"

471
00:33:29.507 --> 00:33:31.259
The overnight operator said.

472
00:33:31.342 --> 00:33:34.470
"I don't know. but the agent
who was working the wire.

473
00:33:34.554 --> 00:33:35.763
he's gonna call you."

474
00:33:37.974 --> 00:33:41.227
You feel like you're gonna have a stroke.
At least that's the way I felt.

475
00:33:42.478 --> 00:33:44.022
Finally. I got the call.

476
00:33:44.647 --> 00:33:48.818
and I was told that it was
Joey Ciancaglini that was shot.

477
00:33:48.901 --> 00:33:50.737
It didn't take police long to realize

478
00:33:50.820 --> 00:33:52.989
that they had another Mob hit
on their hands.

479
00:33:53.072 --> 00:33:55.867
This time. it was inside
this luncheonette in Grays Ferry.

480
00:33:57.702 --> 00:33:59.996
I turned the TV on.
and I thought I was dreaming

481
00:34:00.079 --> 00:34:03.708
because the local news stations
all had cameras

482
00:34:03.791 --> 00:34:05.918
focused on this luncheonette.

483
00:34:06.502 --> 00:34:09.255
And they were talking about this Mob hit
that had just occurred

484
00:34:09.964 --> 00:34:12.842
within an hour or two
after we had left that place that night.

485
00:34:13.342 --> 00:34:17.055
Cherry Hill resident Joseph Ciancaglini
was shot five times.

486
00:34:17.138 --> 00:34:20.933
Police say that he works
for Philadelphia Mob boss John Stanfa.

487
00:34:22.643 --> 00:34:26.731
Joseph Ciancaglini is grievously injured
and gets taken to the hospital.

488
00:34:29.400 --> 00:34:34.280
I remember the paramedic saying
that Joey wanted to blow his nose.

489
00:34:34.363 --> 00:34:37.116
but they did not allow him
because they were afraid

490
00:34:37.200 --> 00:34:42.288
he was going to blow literally
parts of his brains out of his nostrils.

491
00:34:48.211 --> 00:34:51.839
I remember hearing
the screams of the waitress.

492
00:34:53.049 --> 00:34:56.469
You know. it was just… awful.

493
00:35:02.100 --> 00:35:05.019
Here was this absolutely horrific act.

494
00:35:05.520 --> 00:35:09.398
It clearly did not appear to be a robbery.
Nothing was taken.

495
00:35:10.191 --> 00:35:13.694
So we needed to examine
the tape from the diner.

496
00:35:28.584 --> 00:35:31.170
We saw a car
with three people jumping out.

497
00:35:31.254 --> 00:35:33.172
and we saw a car behind it.

498
00:35:33.256 --> 00:35:35.883
which was. like.
definitely. like. a protection car.

499
00:35:36.759 --> 00:35:41.639
It just takes a number of seconds.
It can't be more than ten seconds.

500
00:35:42.140 --> 00:35:44.642
They run in. they shoot. and they run out.

501
00:35:50.189 --> 00:35:53.818
We figured one of the shooters
was part of the Young Turks.

502
00:35:54.443 --> 00:35:58.030
but it was just a dark. grainy video.

503
00:35:58.114 --> 00:36:01.325
There's no way you could identify
who the gunmen were.

504
00:36:03.619 --> 00:36:07.290
It was very frustrating
because here we had everything.

505
00:36:07.373 --> 00:36:10.459
We had a wiretap. We had a camera.

506
00:36:12.295 --> 00:36:16.382
We had. the first time ever.
a filmed attempted Mob hit.

507
00:36:17.258 --> 00:36:19.010
And we just couldn't prove who did it.

508
00:36:25.683 --> 00:36:27.643
Stanfa. he had come to the point

509
00:36:27.727 --> 00:36:31.772
where he was gonna have to do something
about that younger faction.

510
00:36:31.856 --> 00:36:35.943
I mean. to go
into Stanfa's diner like that

511
00:36:36.027 --> 00:36:38.988
and to pull off a hit so brazen.

512
00:36:39.071 --> 00:36:41.782
you know it's really escalating
at that point.

513
00:36:43.910 --> 00:36:47.997
But at least we could monitor
most of what Stanfa was saying.

514
00:36:50.833 --> 00:36:54.420
One day. we saw Stanfa going
into Sal Avena's office

515
00:36:54.503 --> 00:36:57.757
with Sergio Battaglia.
who was an associate.

516
00:36:58.966 --> 00:37:03.054
Then there was this wiretap interception.
which was…

517
00:37:04.555 --> 00:37:05.681
astounding.

518
00:37:11.437 --> 00:37:14.523
You can hear John Stanfa
and Sergio Battaglia

519
00:37:14.607 --> 00:37:18.277
planning the murder
of Michael Ciancaglini and Joey Merlino.

520
00:37:34.835 --> 00:37:38.464
To hear a Mob boss so angry

521
00:37:38.547 --> 00:37:41.926
that he would describe in detail
how he would kill somebody.

522
00:37:42.009 --> 00:37:44.470
I've never heard of… of that before.

523
00:37:44.553 --> 00:37:48.057
It's always done in code.
"You take care of that matter."

524
00:37:48.557 --> 00:37:50.977
You know.
"Don't bother me with the details."

525
00:38:02.071 --> 00:38:04.740
They were talking about
getting rid of the bodies

526
00:38:04.824 --> 00:38:07.618
and putting it in some type
of ready-made concrete.

527
00:38:07.702 --> 00:38:09.161
which would harden right away.

528
00:38:09.245 --> 00:38:12.540
If that wasn't astounding enough.
Stanfa said…

529
00:38:32.393 --> 00:38:33.686
It was chilling.

530
00:38:35.646 --> 00:38:38.482
We were all shocked.
Shocked beyond belief.

531
00:38:38.566 --> 00:38:42.111
What's going to happen next?
Are things out of control here?

532
00:38:44.947 --> 00:38:46.490
Now it was war.

533
00:38:47.408 --> 00:38:48.659
John Stanfa's desperate.

534
00:38:49.827 --> 00:38:51.746
He needs to kill Joey Merlino.

535
00:38:55.583 --> 00:38:57.293
But he makes a major mistake.

536
00:39:01.672 --> 00:39:05.384
He goes outside of the Mob
and gets someone crazy.

537
00:39:07.053 --> 00:39:08.137
uncontrollable…

538
00:39:10.765 --> 00:39:12.099
and very dangerous.

539
00:39:14.185 --> 00:39:15.603
I mean. I've burned people.

540
00:39:16.979 --> 00:39:17.980
I drilled them.

541
00:39:18.647 --> 00:39:20.399
I will say this. I had no morals.

542
00:39:21.609 --> 00:39:25.071
It was just kill.
Just… just kill. Just… just kill.

543
00:39:25.154 --> 00:39:26.822
And that's what I did.

543
00:39:27.305 --> 00:40:27.275
